    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1957-11-11T08:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1957-11-11T08:00:00-05:00" n="279"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d279">
                <head>279. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Embassy in Tunisia</gloss> to the
                        <gloss type="to">Department of State</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d279fn1">Source: Department of State, Central
                        Files, 772.56/11–1157. Secret; <gloss target="#t_niact1">Niact</gloss>.
                        Repeated to Paris, London, and Tripoli. Received at 10:20 a.m.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="italic">Tunis</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1957-11-11T14:00:00+01:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">November 11, 1957—2 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>460. Mokkadem has just informed me as follows (paragraph 1 <gloss
                        target="#t_Embtel1">Embtel</gloss> 457)<note n="2" xml:id="d279fn2">Telegram
                        457, November 11, stated that the French démarches seemed proof to the
                        Tunisians that France wished to maintain control over arms supplies so as to
                        retain its leverage; that the new government had done nothing to demonstrate
                        its good will toward Tunisia; and that Tunisia insisted that the question of
                        arms was unrelated to its negotiations with France. (<hi rend="italic"
                            >Ibid</hi>.)</note> on direct instructions from <persName
                        corresp="#p_BH1">Bourguiba</persName>: <list>
                        <label>1.</label>
                        <item>In light all factors <persName corresp="#p_BH1">Bourguiba</persName>
                            does not feel able agree additional delay (paragraph 1 <gloss
                                target="#t_Deptel1">Deptel</gloss> 316) for variety reasons (see
                            also paragraph 2 Embassy’s reference telegram): <list>
                                <label>(a)</label>
                                <item>On basis November 12 date fixed by US and <gloss
                                        target="#t_UK1">UK</gloss>, <gloss target="#t_GOT1"
                                        >GOT</gloss> has agreed arrival Egyptian arms “several days”
                                    after November 12. <gloss target="#t_GOT1">GOT</gloss> not sure
                                    exact date but has given green light GOE.</item>
                                <label>(b)</label>
                                <item>
                                    <gloss target="#t_GOT1">GOT</gloss> does not believe <gloss
                                        target="#t_GOF1">GOF</gloss> would or could provide <gloss
                                        target="#t_GOT1">GOT</gloss> with arms on acceptable terms;
                                    its past experience with <gloss target="#t_GOF1">GOF</gloss> re
                                    arms most unsatisfactory: for example, <gloss target="#t_GOF1"
                                        >GOF</gloss> withheld ammunition even for Tunisian Army
                                    training.</item>
                                <label>(c)</label>
                                <item>Psychological point for <gloss target="#t_GOT1">GOT</gloss> is
                                    that Tunisian Army is expression Tunisian sovereignty and French
                                    arms would reinforce impression <gloss target="#t_GOT1"
                                        >GOT</gloss> still under French tutelage.</item>
                                <label>(d)</label>
                                <item>Final point was that of national dignity: <gloss
                                        target="#t_GOT1">GOT</gloss> has been negotiating directly
                                    with <gloss target="#t_USA1">USA</gloss> and <gloss
                                        target="#t_UK1">UK</gloss> re arms. <gloss target="#t_GOT1"
                                        >GOT</gloss> does not particularly welcome addition France
                                    as factor these negotiations.</item>
                            </list>
                        </item>
                        <label>2.</label>
                        <item>I asked whether <gloss target="#t_GOT1">GOT</gloss> would refuse
                            French arms if offered. Mokkadem replied: “We will study carefully any
                            propositions which <gloss target="#t_GOF1">GOF</gloss> may make to
                            us”.</item>
                        <label>3.</label>
                        <item>I asked whether <persName corresp="#p_BH1">Bourguiba</persName> still
                            contemplated maintaining secrecy until his speech November 14. Mokkadem
                            said it was his <pb facs="0766" n="740" xml:id="pg_740"/> understanding
                            that after arrival arms November 12 timing publicity up to <persName
                                corresp="#p_BH1">Bourguiba</persName>.</item>
                        <label>4.</label>
                        <item>In sum, <persName corresp="#p_BH1">Bourguiba</persName> is holding US
                            to its promise deliver arms November 12. <gloss target="#t_Embtel1"
                                >Embtel</gloss> 455<note n="3" xml:id="d279fn3">Telegram 455,
                                November 9, reported that Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_JGL1"
                                    >Jones</persName> informed Mokkadem on November 8 that the arms
                                would come in by air. (<hi rend="italic">Ibid.,</hi>
                                772.56/11–957)</note> gives Tunisian view 5 a.m. November 12 as
                            suitable arrival time.</item>
                        <label>5.</label>
                        <item>
                            <hi rend="italic">Comment</hi>: So far as our relations with <persName
                                corresp="#p_BH1">Bourguiba</persName> are concerned, only delivery
                            as planned will mitigate adverse impression made upon him by US–<gloss
                                target="#t_UK1">UK</gloss> démarche at last minute.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_JGL1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Jones</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
